erwise skew the public debate to their benefit. These tactics are particularly effective before the outbreak of war, when the information gap between leaders and the public is greatest.When resorting to deception, leaders take a calculated risk that the outcome of war will be favorable, expecting the public to adopt a forgiving attitude after victory is secured. The three cases featured in the book—Franklin Roosevelt and World War II, Lyndon Johnson and the Vietnam War, and George W. Bush and the Iraq War—test these claims. Schuessler concludes that democracies are not as constrained in their ability to go to war as we might believe and that deception cannot be ruled out in all cases as contrary to the national interest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDeceptionxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xDeceptionzUnited States. 0aPolitical leadershipzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPolitics and warzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xDeceptionzUnited States. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xDeceptionzUnited States. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aU.S. presidents, leadership, American democracy, American political system, propaganda, information gap, asymmetric information, Franklin Roosevelt, Lyndon Johnson, George W. Bush, foreign policy, domestic policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170162740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501701627423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501701627/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL